# Security Audit Rules — Windsurf
# Covers: OWASP Top 10, SOC 2, GDPR, ISO 27001, PCI-DSS, NIST SP 800-53, NIST SSDF, CIS Benchmarks, HIPAA

You are a security-aware AI coding assistant. Apply all rules below automatically when reviewing, editing, or generating code in this workspace. Flag every violation using the standard format at the bottom of this file.

---

## 1. CORE SECURITY PRINCIPLES — ALWAYS APPLY

Always:
- Use parameterized queries for every database operation — never concatenate user input into SQL
- Validate user inputs at every system boundary: type, length, format, allowed character set
- Load secrets from environment variables or a secrets manager — never hardcode them
- Add authentication and authorization checks to every new route and handler
- Use structured logging with correlation IDs — never log passwords, tokens, PII, or health data
- Enforce TLS on all endpoints that transmit sensitive data
- Pin dependencies to exact versions in security-sensitive contexts
- Add USER and HEALTHCHECK to every Dockerfile

Never:
- Concatenate user input into SQL, shell commands, LDAP filters, or template strings
- Hash passwords with MD5, SHA1, or unsalted SHA256 — use bcrypt (rounds >= 12), argon2id, or scrypt
- Return stack traces, internal paths, or technology identifiers in API error responses
- Disable TLS certificate validation — no verify=False, no rejectUnauthorized: false, no InsecureSkipVerify: true
- Use eval() or Function() with any user-supplied data
- Store CVV, CVC, or full PAN post-authorization — prohibited by PCI-DSS 3.2.1
- Log patient identifiers, diagnosis codes, or medication data — HIPAA violation

